SIMPLE: humanitarian
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Humanitarian
<hw>Hu*man`i*ta"ri*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Theol. & Ch. Hist.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to humanitarians, or to
humanitarianism; <as>as, a <ex>humanitarian</ex> view of Christ's
nature</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Philos.)</fld> <def>Content with right affections
and actions toward man; ethical, as distinguished from religious;
believing in the perfectibility of man's nature without supernatural
aid.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Benevolent; philanthropic.</def>
<mark>[Recent]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Humanitarian</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Humanitarian
<hw>Hu*man`i*ta"ri*an</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From
<er>Humanity</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Theol. & Ch. Hist.)</fld>
<def>One who denies the divinity of Christ, and believes him to have
been merely human.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Philos.)</fld> <def>One who limits the sphere of
duties to human relations and affections, to the exclusion or
disparagement of the religious or spiritual.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>One who is actively concerned in promoting the
welfare of humans and human societies; a philanthropist.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Humanitarianism</ent>⟦br⟧
